Sure, here's an example of batch processing pattern based on Java Spring project:

1. Define your batch processing job:
In Spring Batch, you can define a batch processing job using the `Job` interface. This interface defines a single method, `execute`, which takes a `JobExecution` object as an argument. You can implement this interface in a Java class and define your batch processing logic in the `execute` method.
```java
@Component
public class MyBatchJob implements Job {

    @Autowired
    private Step step1;

    @Override
    public JobExecution execute(JobExecution jobExecution) throws JobExecutionException {
        return new JobExecution(jobExecution.getJobInstance(), jobExecution.getId());
    }

    @Bean
    public Job myJob() {
        return jobBuilderFactory.get("myJob")
                .incrementer(new RunIdIncrementer())
                .start(step1)
                .build();
    }
}
```
2. Define your batch processing steps:
In Spring Batch, a job is composed of one or more steps, each of which represents a unit of work. You can define a step by implementing the `Step` interface in a Java class and defining your step logic in the `execute` method. You can then wire up the steps in your job using the `JobBuilder`.
```less
@Component
public class MyBatchStep implements Step {

    @Override
    public void execute(StepExecution stepExecution) throws JobInterruptedException {
        // your step logic here
    }

    @Bean
    public Step step1() {
        return stepBuilderFactory.get("step1")
                .tasklet(new MyBatchStep())
                .build();
    }
}
```
3. Configure your job and steps:
You can configure your job and steps using Spring Batch's `JobBuilderFactory` and `StepBuilderFactory`. These classes provide methods for configuring various aspects of your job and steps, such as the name, description, and transaction management.
```less
@Configuration
@EnableBatchProcessing
public class BatchConfig {

    @Autowired
    private JobBuilderFactory jobBuilderFactory;

    @Autowired
    private StepBuilderFactory stepBuilderFactory;

    @Bean
    public Job myJob() {
        return jobBuilderFactory.get("myJob")
                .incrementer(new RunIdIncrementer())
                .start(step1())
                .build();
    }

    @Bean
    public Step step1() {
        return stepBuilderFactory.get("step1")
                .tasklet(new MyBatchStep())
                .build();
    }
}
```
4. Run your job:
To run your batch processing job, you can use Spring Batch's `JobLauncher` interface. You can inject an instance of this interface into your Java class and call the `run` method to start your job. The `run` method returns a `JobExecution` object, which you can use to monitor the status of your job.
```java
@Component
public class MyBatchJobRunner {

    @Autowired
    private JobLauncher jobLauncher;

    @Autowired
    private Job myJob;

    public void runJob() throws Exception {
        JobExecution jobExecution = jobLauncher.run(myJob, new JobParameters());

        while (jobExecution.isRunning()) {
            // wait for job to complete
        }

        System.out.println("Job completed with status: " + jobExecution.getStatus());
    }
}
```
This is just a basic example of batch processing using Spring Batch. Depending on your specific use case, you may need to implement additional features such as item readers/writers, processors, and exception handling.

