fetch('image-url')
  .then(response => response.blob())
  .then(blob => {
    // Do something with the image blob
  });
```
The `fetch` function sends a request to the specified URL and returns a `Promise` that resolves to a `Response` object. The `Response` object has a `blob` method that returns a `Promise` that resolves to a `Blob` object representing the image data.

You can then use the `Blob` object to do something with the image data, such as creating an `<img>` element and setting its `src` attribute to a `URL.createObjectURL()` of the `Blob` object.
```
const imgElement = document.createElement('img');
imgElement.src = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
document.body.appendChild(imgElement);
```
Alternatively, you can use the `Response.arrayBuffer` method to get the image data as an `ArrayBuffer`, which you can then convert to a typed array and pass to the `createImageBitmap` function to create an `ImageBitmap` object.
```
fetch('image-url')
  .then(response => response.arrayBuffer())
  .then(arrayBuffer => {
    return createImageBitmap(new Uint8Array(arrayBuffer));
  })
  .then(imageBitmap => {
    // Do something with the image bitmap
  });
```
Note that the `fetch` function is only supported in modern browsers. If you need to support older browsers, you may need to use an alternative approach such as using the `XMLHttpRequest` object.

