It sounds like your NodeJS app is encountering unhandled exceptions or errors that are not being properly handled, leading to an infinite loading state. Fortunately, there are several solutions you can try to address this issue without having to edit every single function for error handling.

One solution is to use a global error handler that catches any unhandled exceptions or errors in your NodeJS app. You can implement this by attaching an event listener to the `process` object in NodeJS, like so:
```javascript
process.on('uncaughtException', function (err) {
  console.error('Uncaught Exception:', err);
  // Do any necessary cleanup, logging, or other handling here
  process.exit(1); // Exit the process to prevent further execution
});
```
With this global error handler in place, any unhandled exceptions or errors will be caught and logged to the console, and you can add any necessary cleanup or handling logic before exiting the process.

Another solution is to use a middleware function that adds error handling to all your routes automatically. You can do this by defining a middleware function that catches any errors thrown by your route handlers and passes them along to the next middleware function or error handler, like so:
```javascript
function errorHandler(err, req, res, next) {
  console.error('Error:', err);
  res.status(500).send('Internal Server Error');
}

app.use(function(req, res, next) {
  try {
    next();
  } catch (err) {
    errorHandler(err, req, res, next);
  }
});
```
With this middleware function in place, any errors thrown by your route handlers will be caught and passed along to the error handler function, which can log the error and send an appropriate response to the client.

I hope these solutions help you address the infinite loading issue in your NodeJS app!

